## Key Findings

### Attack Evidence
![DVWA showing /etc/passwd contents](screenshots/01-dvwa-etc-passwd-traversal.png)

The screenshot shows the File Inclusion vulnerability successfully displaying the contents of `/etc/passwd`. The file contains sensitive system information including:
- Root account details
- System service accounts
- User login shells

### Forensic Evidence
![Apache2 access log showing directory traversal payload](screenshots/02-apache-log-directory-traversal.png)

The Apache access log entry reveals:
```
192.168.4.43 - - [19/Jan/2026:13:01:21 -0500] "GET /dvwa/vulnerabilities/fi/?page=../../../../../etc/passwd HTTP/1.1" 200 5674 "-"
```

**Log Analysis:**
- **Source IP:** 192.168.4.43 (attacker/Host PC)
- **Timestamp:** 19/Jan/2026 13:01:21
- **HTTP Method:** GET
- **Vulnerable Path:** `/dvwa/vulnerabilities/fi/`
- **Payload:** `?page=../../../../../etc/passwd`
- **Response Code:** 200 (successful)
- **Bytes Returned:** 5674 (size of /etc/passwd file)

The HTTP 200 response code indicates the attack succeeded—the server processed the request and returned the requested file.

